But then-deputy White House counsel Fred Fielding, onetime Nixon aide Alexander Haig, speechwriter Patrick Buchanan and many others who have been mentioned as possible candidates -- in some cases based on circumstantial evidence at best -- may finally face fewer questions about the famous disclosures of over three decades ago. Ferreting out Deep Throat's identity has long been a favorite topic in Washington and beyond, and the search has engaged former Nixon administration officials who dealt with the consequences of his leaks, intrepid journalism students eager to solve one of a prior generation's abiding enigmas, and many an armchair sleuth. 